drh added on 2021-06-25 14:27:25:
In the SQL below, the first query (with the NOT INDEXED clause) gets the
correct answer, but the second query does not:

CREATE TABLE t1(a,b,c);
CREATE INDEX t1abc ON t1(a,b,c);
CREATE INDEX t1bca on t1(b,c,a);
INSERT INTO t1 VALUES(56,1119,1115);
INSERT INTO t1 VALUES(57,1147,1137);
INSERT INTO t1 VALUES(100,1050,1023);
INSERT INTO t1 VALUES(101,1050,1023);
ANALYZE sqlite_schema;
INSERT INTO sqlite_stat1 VALUES('t1','t1abc','358677 2 2 1');
INSERT INTO sqlite_stat1 VALUES('t1','t1bca','358677 4 2 1');
ANALYZE sqlite_schema;
SELECT * FROM t1 NOT INDEXED
 WHERE (b = 1137 AND c IN (97, 98))
    OR (b = 1119 AND c IN (1115, 1023));
SELECT * FROM t1
 WHERE (b = 1137 AND c IN (97, 98))
    OR (b = 1119 AND c IN (1115, 1023));

This problem was reported to us by private email from Frank Aurich.
drh added on 2021-06-25 14:49:38:
Problem was introduced by the OP_SeekScan optimization of
check-in [4a43430fd23f8835].  It thus affects version 3.34.0, 3.35.0,
and 3.36.0.
The first OR-clause term is leaving the t1bca cursor in an unusual
state which causes the OP_SeekScqan opcode in the
second OR-clause term to malfunction.  The
solution is to fix the OP_ReopenIdx opcode so that it clears the
cursor.
Fixed by check-in [d4bf5243f2bf0a2b].
